# OpenAPI (utoipa) conventions

Code-first via `utoipa`. Spec: `GET /openapi.json`. UI: Scalar `GET /docs`.

## Info + tags (`openapi.rs`)

- `info.title` / `version` / `description` must be real product copy (what the API is, auth model in 2–3 sentences).
- Every tag needs a one-line `description` (audience + scope).
- Document security schemes with a human description (what token type, where it comes from).

## Every `#[utoipa::path]`

Required:

- `summary` — short verb phrase (e.g. `Create Dashboard Session`)
- `description` — when to call it, auth, side effects, caveats
- `operation_id` — stable `snake_case` (`auth_login`, `projects_create`)
- `tag` — one of the registered tags
- `responses` — every status the handler returns, with clear `description`
- `security(...)` when the route needs a session / key

Prefer English in OpenAPI text (matches code / Scalar consumers).

## Schemas (`ToSchema`)

- Struct: rustdoc (`/// ...`) becomes schema description; add `#[schema(example = json!(...))]` when useful.
- Fields: rustdoc + `#[schema(example = ..., format = "...")]` for emails, passwords, ULIDs, tokens.
- Enums / role strings: document allowed values in the field description (`owner` \| `admin` \| `member`).
- One-time secrets (API keys, plaintext passwords in examples): mark clearly in description; use **dev** example values only (`dev@indiebase.com`, `ib_pub_…` shape).

```rust
/// Credentials for Dashboard Session login.
#[derive(ToSchema)]
#[schema(example = json!({"email":"dev@indiebase.com","password":"dev@indiebase.com"}))]
pub struct LoginRequest {
    /// Platform user email (normalized to lowercase).
    #[schema(example = "dev@indiebase.com", format = "email")]
    pub email: String,
    /// Account password.
    #[schema(example = "dev@indiebase.com", format = "password")]
    pub password: String,
}
```

## Do not

- Leave bare `description = "OK"` / empty summaries.
- Expose internal error strings as the only 500 docs; prefer generic Internal.
- Skip registering new schemas in `openapi.rs` `components(schemas(...))`.
